# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: columnar-format
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:columnar-format/apache-orc] In February 2013, the Optimized Row Columnar (ORC) file format was announced by Hortonworks in collaboration with Facebook.
[src:columnar-format/apache-orc] A calendar month later, the Apache Parquet format was announced, developed by Cloudera and Twitter.
[src:columnar-format/apache-orc] Apache ORC format is widely supported including Amazon Web Services' Glue,Google Cloud Platform's BigQuery, and Pandas (software).
[src:columnar-format/apache-parquet] The open-source project to build Apache Parquet began as a joint effort between Twitter and Cloudera using the record shredding and assembly algorithm as described in Google's Dremel.
[src:columnar-format/apache-parquet] Parquet was designed as an improvement on the Trevni columnar storage format created by Doug Cutting, the creator of Hadoop.
[src:columnar-format/apache-parquet] 'small compartment') refers to a style of decorative flooring and was chosen to "evoke the bottom layer of a database with an interesting layout".
[src:columnar-format/apache-parquet] The first version, Apache Parquet 1.0, was released in July 2013.
[src:columnar-format/apache-parquet] Since April 27, 2015, Apache Parquet has been a top-level Apache Software Foundation (ASF)-sponsored project.
[src:columnar-format/apache-parquet] Apache Parquet is implemented using the record-shredding and assembly algorithm, which accommodates the complex data structures that can be used to store data.
[src:columnar-format/apache-parquet] Apache Parquet is implemented using the Apache Thrift framework, which increases its flexibility; it can work with a number of programming languages like C++, Java, Python, PHP, etc.
[src:columnar-format/apache-parquet] As of August 2015, Parquet supports the big-data-processing frameworks including Apache Hive, Apache Drill, Apache Impala, Apache Crunch, Apache Pig, Cascading, Presto and Apache Spark.
[src:columnar-format/apache-parquet] It is one of the external data formats used by the pandas Python data manipulation and analysis library.
[src:columnar-format/apache-parquet] In Parquet, compression is performed column by column, which enables different encoding schemes to be used for text and integer data.
[src:columnar-format/apache-parquet] This strategy also keeps the door open for newer and better encoding schemes to be implemented as they are invented.
[src:columnar-format/apache-parquet] Parquet supports various compression formats: snappy, gzip, LZO, brotli, zstd, and LZ4.
[src:columnar-format/apache-parquet] Parquet has an automatic dictionary encoding enabled dynamically for data with a *small* number of unique values (i.e. below 105) that enables significant compression and boosts processing speed.
[src:columnar-format/apache-parquet] Storage of integers is usually done with dedicated 32 or 64 bits per integer.
[src:columnar-format/apache-parquet] For small integers, packing multiple integers into the same space makes storage more efficient.
[src:columnar-format/apache-parquet] To optimize storage of multiple occurrences of the same value, run-length encoding is used, which is where a single value is stored once along with the number of occurrences.
[src:columnar-format/apache-parquet] Parquet implements a hybrid of bit packing and RLE, in which the encoding switches based on which produces the best compression results.
[src:columnar-format/apache-parquet] This strategy works well for certain types of integer data and combines well with dictionary encoding.
[src:columnar-format/apache-parquet] Parquet is widely used as the underlying file format in modern cloud-based data lake architectures.
[src:columnar-format/apache-parquet] Cloud storage systems such as Amazon S3, Azure Data Lake Storage, and Google Cloud Storage commonly store data in Parquet format due to its efficient columnar representation and retrieval capabilities.
[src:columnar-format/apache-parquet] Data lakehouse frameworks—including Apache Iceberg, Delta Lake, and Apache Hudi —build an additional metadata layer on top of Parquet files to support features such as schema evolution, time-travel queries, and ACID-compliant transactions.
[src:columnar-format/apache-parquet] In these architectures, Parquet files serve as the immutable storage layer while the table formats manage data versioning and transactional integrity.
[src:columnar-format/apache-parquet] Apache Parquet is comparable to RCFile and Optimized Row Columnar (ORC) file formats — all three fall under the category of columnar data storage within the Hadoop ecosystem.
[src:columnar-format/apache-parquet] They all have better compression and encoding with improved read performance at the cost of slower writes.
[src:columnar-format/apache-parquet] In addition to these features, Apache Parquet supports limited schema evolution, i.e., the schema can be modified according to the changes in the data.
[src:columnar-format/apache-parquet] It also provides the ability to add new columns and merge schemas that do not conflict.
[src:columnar-format/apache-parquet] Apache Arrow is designed as an in-memory complement to on-disk columnar formats like Parquet and ORC.
[src:columnar-format/apache-parquet] The Arrow and Parquet projects include libraries that allow for reading and writing between the two formats.
[src:columnar-format/column-oriented-dbms] The choice of data orientation is a trade-off and an architectural decision in databases, query engines, and numerical simulations.
[src:columnar-format/column-oriented-dbms] As a result of these tradeoffs, row-oriented formats are more commonly used in online transaction processing (OLTP) and column-oriented formats are more commonly used in online analytical processing (OLAP).
[src:columnar-format/column-oriented-dbms] Examples of column-oriented formats include Apache ORC, Apache Parquet, Apache Arrow, formats used by BigQuery, Amazon Redshift and Snowflake.
[src:columnar-format/column-oriented-dbms] Predominant examples of row-oriented formats include CSV, formats used in most relational databases (Oracle, MySQL etc.), the in-memory format of Apache Spark, and Apache Avro.
[src:columnar-format/column-oriented-dbms] Tabular data is two dimensional — data is modeled as rows and columns.
[src:columnar-format/column-oriented-dbms] However, computer systems represent data in a linear memory model, both in-disk and in-memory.
[src:columnar-format/column-oriented-dbms] Therefore, a table in a linear memory model requires mapping its two-dimensional scheme into a one-dimensional space.
[src:columnar-format/column-oriented-dbms] Data orientation is to the decision taken in this mapping.
[src:columnar-format/column-oriented-dbms] There are two prominent mappings: row-oriented and column-oriented.
[src:columnar-format/column-oriented-dbms] I.e. each row of the table is located one after the other.
[src:columnar-format/column-oriented-dbms] In this orientation, values in the same row are close in space (e.g. similar address in an addressable space).
[src:columnar-format/column-oriented-dbms] I.e. each column of the table is located one after the other.
[src:columnar-format/column-oriented-dbms] In this orientation, values on the same column are close in space (e.g. similar address in an addressable space).
[src:columnar-format/column-oriented-dbms] See list of column-oriented DBMSes for more examples.
[src:columnar-format/column-oriented-dbms] Data orientation is an important architectural decision of systems handling data because it results in important tradeoffs in performance and storage.
[src:columnar-format/column-oriented-dbms] Below are selected dimensions of this tradeoff.
[src:columnar-format/column-oriented-dbms] Row-oriented benefits from fast random access of rows.
[src:columnar-format/column-oriented-dbms] Column-oriented benefits from fast random access of columns.
[src:columnar-format/column-oriented-dbms] In both cases, this is the result of fewer page or cache misses when accessing the data.
[src:columnar-format/column-oriented-dbms] Row-oriented benefits from fast insertion of a new row.
[src:columnar-format/column-oriented-dbms] Column-oriented benefits from fast insertion of a new column.
[src:columnar-format/column-oriented-dbms] This dimension is an important reason why row-oriented formats are more commonly used in online transaction processing (OLTP), as it results in faster transactions in comparison to column-oriented.
[src:columnar-format/column-oriented-dbms] Row-oriented benefits from fast access under a filter.
[src:columnar-format/column-oriented-dbms] Column-oriented benefits from fast access under a projection.
[src:columnar-format/column-oriented-dbms] Column-oriented benefits from fast analytics operations.
[src:columnar-format/column-oriented-dbms] This is the result of being able to leverage SIMD instructions.
[src:columnar-format/column-oriented-dbms] Column-oriented benefits from smaller uncompressed size.
[src:columnar-format/column-oriented-dbms] This is the result of the possibility that this orientation offers to represent certain data types with dedicated encodings.
[src:columnar-format/column-oriented-dbms] For example, a table of 128 rows with a Boolean column requires 128 bytes in a row-oriented format (one byte per Boolean) but 128 bits (16 bytes) in a column-oriented format (via a bitmap).
[src:columnar-format/column-oriented-dbms] Another example is the use of run-length encoding to encode a column.
[src:columnar-format/column-oriented-dbms] Column-oriented benefits from smaller compressed size.
[src:columnar-format/column-oriented-dbms] This is the result of a higher homogeneity within a column than within multiple rows.
[src:columnar-format/column-oriented-dbms] Because both orientations represent the same data, it is possible to convert a row-oriented dataset to a column-oriented dataset and vice versa at the expense of compute.
[src:columnar-format/column-oriented-dbms] In particular, advanced query engines often leverage each orientation's advantages, and convert from one orientation to the other as part of their execution.
[src:columnar-format/data-compression] In information theory, **data compression**, **source coding**, or **bit-rate reduction** is the process of encoding information using fewer bits than the original representation.
[src:columnar-format/data-compression] Any particular compression is either lossy or lossless.
[src:columnar-format/data-compression] Lossless compression reduces bits by identifying and eliminating statistical redundancy.
[src:columnar-format/data-compression] No information is lost in lossless compression.
[src:columnar-format/data-compression] Lossy compression reduces bits by removing unnecessary or less important information.
[src:columnar-format/data-compression] Typically, a device that performs data compression is referred to as an encoder, and one that performs the reversal of the process (decompression) as a decoder.
[src:columnar-format/data-compression] The process of reducing the size of a data file is often referred to as data compression.
[src:columnar-format/data-compression] In the context of data transmission, it is called source coding: encoding is done at the source of the data before it is stored or transmitted.
[src:columnar-format/data-compression] Source coding should not be confused with channel coding, for error detection and correction or line coding, the means for mapping data onto a signal.
[src:columnar-format/data-compression] Data compression algorithms present a space–time complexity trade-off between the bytes needed to store or transmit information, and the computational resources needed to perform the encoding and decoding.
[src:columnar-format/data-compression] The design of data compression schemes involves balancing the degree of compression, the amount of distortion introduced (when using lossy data compression), and the computational resources or time required to compress and decompress the data.
[src:columnar-format/data-compression] Lossless data compression algorithms usually exploit statistical redundancy to represent data without losing any information, so that the process is reversible.
[src:columnar-format/data-compression] Lossless compression is possible because most real-world data exhibits statistical redundancy.
[src:columnar-format/data-compression] For example, an image may have areas of color that do not change over several pixels; instead of coding "red pixel, red pixel, ..." the data may be encoded as "279 red pixels".
[src:columnar-format/data-compression] This is a basic example of run-length encoding; there are many schemes to reduce file size by eliminating redundancy.
[src:columnar-format/data-compression] The Lempel–Ziv (LZ) compression methods are among the most popular algorithms for lossless storage.
[src:columnar-format/data-compression] DEFLATE is a variation on LZ optimized for decompression speed and compression ratio, but compression can be slow.
[src:columnar-format/data-compression] In the mid-1980s, following work by Terry Welch, the Lempel–Ziv–Welch (LZW) algorithm rapidly became the method of choice for most general-purpose compression systems.
[src:columnar-format/data-compression] LZW is used in GIF images, programs such as PKZIP, and hardware devices such as modems.
[src:columnar-format/data-compression] LZ methods use a table-based compression model where table entries are substituted for repeated strings of data.
[src:columnar-format/data-compression] For most LZ methods, this table is generated dynamically from earlier data in the input.
[src:columnar-format/data-compression] The table itself is often Huffman encoded.
[src:columnar-format/data-compression] Grammar-based codes like this can compress highly repetitive input extremely effectively, for instance, a biological data collection of the same or closely related species, a huge versioned document collection, internet archival, etc.
[src:columnar-format/data-compression] The basic task of grammar-based codes is constructing a context-free grammar deriving a single string.
[src:columnar-format/data-compression] Other practical grammar compression algorithms include Sequitur and Re-Pair.
[src:columnar-format/data-compression] The strongest modern lossless compressors use probabilistic models, such as prediction by partial matching.
[src:columnar-format/data-compression] The Burrows–Wheeler transform can also be viewed as an indirect form of statistical modelling.
[src:columnar-format/data-compression] In a further refinement of the direct use of probabilistic modelling, statistical estimates can be coupled to an algorithm called arithmetic coding.
[src:columnar-format/data-compression] Arithmetic coding is a more modern coding technique that uses the mathematical calculations of a finite-state machine to produce a string of encoded bits from a series of input data symbols.
[src:columnar-format/data-compression] It can achieve superior compression compared to other techniques, such as the better-known Huffman algorithm.
[src:columnar-format/data-compression] It uses an internal memory state to avoid the need to perform a one-to-one mapping of individual input symbols to distinct representations that use an integer number of bits, and it clears out the internal memory only after encoding the entire string of data symbols.
[src:columnar-format/data-compression] Arithmetic coding applies especially well to adaptive data compression tasks where the statistics vary and are context-dependent, as it can be easily coupled with an adaptive model of the probability distribution of the input data.
[src:columnar-format/data-compression] An early example of the use of arithmetic coding was in an optional (but not widely used) feature of the JPEG image coding standard.
[src:columnar-format/data-compression] It has since been applied in various other designs including H.263, H.264/MPEG-4 AVC and HEVC for video coding.
[src:columnar-format/data-compression] Archive software typically has the ability to adjust the "dictionary size", where a larger size demands more random-access memory during compression and decompression, but compresses more strongly, especially on repeating patterns in files' content.
[src:columnar-format/data-compression] In the late 1980s, digital images became more common, and standards for lossless image compression emerged.
[src:columnar-format/data-compression] In the early 1990s, lossy compression methods began to be widely used.
[src:columnar-format/data-compression] In these schemes, some loss of information is accepted as dropping nonessential detail can save storage space.
[src:columnar-format/data-compression] There is a corresponding trade-off between preserving information and reducing size.
[src:columnar-format/data-compression] Lossy data compression schemes are designed based on research on how people perceive the data in question.
[src:columnar-format/data-compression] For example, the human eye is more sensitive to subtle variations in luminance than it is to the variations in color.
[src:columnar-format/data-compression] JPEG image compression works in part by rounding off nonessential bits of information.
[src:columnar-format/data-compression] A number of popular compression formats exploit these perceptual differences, including psychoacoustics for sound, and psychovisuals for images and video.
[src:columnar-format/data-compression] Most forms of lossy compression are based on transform coding, especially the discrete cosine transform (DCT).
[src:columnar-format/data-compression] It was first proposed in 1972 by Nasir Ahmed, who then developed a working algorithm with T.
[src:columnar-format/data-compression] Rao in 1973, before introducing it in January 1974.
[src:columnar-format/data-compression] DCT is the most widely used lossy compression method, and is used in multimedia formats for images (such as JPEG and HEIF), video (such as MPEG, AVC and HEVC) and audio (such as MP3, AAC and Vorbis).
[src:columnar-format/data-compression] Lossy image compression is used in digital cameras, to increase storage capacities.
[src:columnar-format/data-compression] Similarly, DVDs, Blu-ray and streaming video use lossy video coding formats.
[src:columnar-format/data-compression] Lossy compression is extensively used in video.
[src:columnar-format/data-compression] In lossy audio compression, methods of psychoacoustics are used to remove non-audible (or less audible) components of the audio signal.
[src:columnar-format/data-compression] Compression of human speech is often performed with even more specialized techniques; speech coding is distinguished as a separate discipline from general-purpose audio compression.
[src:columnar-format/data-compression] Speech coding is used in internet telephony, for example, audio compression is used for CD ripping and is decoded by the audio players.
[src:columnar-format/data-compression] Lossy compression can cause generation loss.
[src:columnar-format/data-compression] The theoretical basis for compression is provided by information theory and, more specifically, Shannon's source coding theorem; domain-specific theories include algorithmic information theory for lossless compression and rate–distortion theory for lossy compression.
[src:columnar-format/data-compression] These areas of study were essentially created by Claude Shannon, who published fundamental papers on the topic in the late 1940s and early 1950s.
[src:columnar-format/data-compression] Other topics associated with compression include coding theory and statistical inference.
[src:columnar-format/data-compression] There is a close connection between machine learning and compression.
[src:columnar-format/data-compression] A system that predicts the posterior probabilities of a sequence given its entire history can be used for optimal data compression (by using arithmetic coding on the output distribution).
[src:columnar-format/data-compression] Conversely, an optimal compressor can be used for prediction (by finding the symbol that compresses best, given the previous history).
[src:columnar-format/data-compression] This equivalence has been used as a justification for using data compression as a benchmark for "general intelligence".
[src:columnar-format/data-compression] An alternative view can show compression algorithms implicitly map strings into implicit feature space vectors, and compression-based similarity measures compute similarity within these feature spaces.
[src:columnar-format/data-compression] For each compressor C(.) we define an associated vector space ℵ, such that C(.) maps an input string x, corresponding to the vector norm ||~x||.
[src:columnar-format/data-compression] An exhaustive examination of the feature spaces underlying all compression algorithms is precluded by space; instead, feature vectors chooses to examine three representative lossless compression methods, LZW, LZ77, and PPM.
[src:columnar-format/data-compression] According to AIXI theory, a connection more directly explained in Hutter Prize, the best possible compression of x is the smallest possible software that generates x.
[src:columnar-format/data-compression] For example, in that model, a zip file's compressed size includes both the zip file and the unzipping software, since you can not unzip it without both, but there may be an even smaller combined form.
[src:columnar-format/data-compression] Examples of AI-powered audio/video compression software include NVIDIA Maxine, AIVC.
[src:columnar-format/data-compression] Examples of software that can perform AI-powered image compression include OpenCV, TensorFlow, MATLAB's Image Processing Toolbox (IPT) and High-Fidelity Generative Image Compression.
[src:columnar-format/data-compression] In unsupervised machine learning, k-means clustering can be utilized to compress data by grouping similar data points into clusters.
[src:columnar-format/data-compression] This technique simplifies handling extensive datasets that lack predefined labels and finds widespread use in fields such as image compression.
[src:columnar-format/data-compression] Data compression aims to reduce the size of data files, enhancing storage efficiency and speeding up data transmission.
[src:columnar-format/data-compression] K-means clustering, an unsupervised machine learning algorithm, is employed to partition a dataset into a specified number of clusters, k, each represented by the centroid of its points.
[src:columnar-format/data-compression] This process condenses extensive datasets into a more compact set of representative points.
[src:columnar-format/data-compression] Particularly beneficial in image and signal processing, k-means clustering aids in data reduction by replacing groups of data points with their centroids, thereby preserving the core information of the original data while significantly decreasing the required storage space.
[src:columnar-format/data-compression] Large language models (LLMs) are also efficient lossless data compressors on some data sets, as demonstrated by DeepMind's research with the Chinchilla 70B model.
[src:columnar-format/data-compression] Developed by DeepMind, Chinchilla 70B effectively compressed data, outperforming conventional methods such as Portable Network Graphics (PNG) for images and Free Lossless Audio Codec (FLAC) for audio.
[src:columnar-format/data-compression] It achieved compression of image and audio data to 43.4% and 16.4% of their original sizes, respectively.
[src:columnar-format/data-compression] There is, however, some reason to be concerned that the data set used for testing overlaps the LLM training data set, making it possible that the Chinchilla 70B model is only an efficient compression tool on data it has already been trained on.
[src:columnar-format/data-compression] Data compression can be viewed as a special case of data differencing.
[src:columnar-format/data-compression] This is the same as considering absolute entropy (corresponding to data compression) as a special case of relative entropy (corresponding to data differencing) with no initial data.
[src:columnar-format/data-compression] The term *differential compression* is used to emphasize the data differencing connection.
[src:columnar-format/data-compression] Entropy coding originated in the 1940s with the introduction of Shannon–Fano coding, the basis for Huffman coding which was developed in 1950.
[src:columnar-format/data-compression] Transform coding dates back to the late 1960s, with the introduction of fast Fourier transform (FFT) coding in 1968 and the Hadamard transform in 1969.
[src:columnar-format/data-compression] An important image compression technique is the discrete cosine transform (DCT), a technique developed in the early 1970s.
[src:columnar-format/data-compression] DCT is the basis for JPEG, a lossy compression format which was introduced by the Joint Photographic Experts Group (JPEG) in 1992.
[src:columnar-format/data-compression] JPEG greatly reduces the amount of data required to represent an image at the cost of a relatively small reduction in image quality and has become the most widely used image file format.
[src:columnar-format/data-compression] Its highly efficient DCT-based compression algorithm was largely responsible for the wide proliferation of digital images and digital photos.
[src:columnar-format/data-compression] Lempel–Ziv–Welch (LZW) is a lossless compression algorithm developed in 1984.
[src:columnar-format/data-compression] It is used in the GIF format, introduced in 1987.
[src:columnar-format/data-compression] DEFLATE, a lossless compression algorithm specified in 1996, is used in the Portable Network Graphics (PNG) format.
[src:columnar-format/data-compression] Wavelet compression, the use of wavelets in image compression, began after the development of DCT coding.
[src:columnar-format/data-compression] The JPEG 2000 standard was introduced in 2000.
[src:columnar-format/data-compression] In contrast to the DCT algorithm used by the original JPEG format, JPEG 2000 instead uses discrete wavelet transform (DWT) algorithms.
[src:columnar-format/data-compression] JPEG 2000 technology, which includes the Motion JPEG 2000 extension, was selected as the video coding standard for digital cinema in 2004.
[src:columnar-format/data-compression] Audio data compression, not to be confused with dynamic range compression, has the potential to reduce the transmission bandwidth and storage requirements of audio data.
[src:columnar-format/data-compression] Audio compression formats compression algorithms are implemented in software as audio codecs.
[src:columnar-format/data-compression] In both lossy and lossless compression, information redundancy is reduced, using methods such as coding, quantization, DCT and linear prediction to reduce the amount of information used to represent the uncompressed data.
[src:columnar-format/data-compression] Lossy audio compression algorithms provide higher compression and are used in numerous audio applications including Vorbis and MP3.
[src:columnar-format/data-compression] These algorithms almost all rely on psychoacoustics to eliminate or reduce fidelity of less audible sounds, thereby reducing the space required to store or transmit them.
[src:columnar-format/data-compression] The acceptable trade-off between loss of audio quality and transmission or storage size depends upon the application.
[src:columnar-format/data-compression] For example, one 640 MB compact disc (CD) holds approximately one hour of uncompressed high fidelity music, less than 2 hours of music compressed losslessly, or 7 hours of music compressed in the MP3 format at a medium bit rate.
[src:columnar-format/data-compression] A digital sound recorder can typically store around 200 hours of clearly intelligible speech in 640 MB.
[src:columnar-format/data-compression] Lossless audio compression produces a representation of digital data that can be decoded to an exact digital duplicate of the original.
[src:columnar-format/data-compression] Compression ratios are around 50–60% of the original size, which is similar to those for generic lossless data compression.
[src:columnar-format/data-compression] Lossless codecs use curve fitting or linear prediction as a basis for estimating the signal.
[src:columnar-format/data-compression] Parameters describing the estimation and the difference between the estimation and the actual signal are coded separately.
[src:columnar-format/data-compression] A number of lossless audio compression formats exist.
[src:columnar-format/data-compression] See list of lossless codecs for a listing.
[src:columnar-format/data-compression] Some formats are associated with a distinct system, such as Direct Stream Transfer, used in Super Audio CD and Meridian Lossless Packing, used in DVD-Audio, Dolby TrueHD, Blu-ray and HD DVD.
[src:columnar-format/data-compression] Some audio file formats feature a combination of a lossy format and a lossless correction; this allows stripping the correction to easily obtain a lossy file.
[src:columnar-format/data-compression] Such formats include MPEG-4 SLS (Scalable to Lossless), WavPack, and OptimFROG DualStream.
[src:columnar-format/data-compression] When audio files are to be processed, either by further compression or for editing, it is desirable to work from an unchanged original (uncompressed or losslessly compressed).
[src:columnar-format/data-compression] Processing of a lossily compressed file for some purpose usually produces a final result inferior to the creation of the same compressed file from an uncompressed original.
[src:columnar-format/data-compression] In addition to sound editing or mixing, lossless audio compression is often used for archival storage, or as master copies.
[src:columnar-format/data-compression] Lossy audio compression is used in a wide range of applications.
[src:columnar-format/data-compression] In addition to standalone audio-only applications of file playback in MP3 players or computers, digitally compressed audio streams are used in most video DVDs, digital television, streaming media on the Internet, satellite and cable radio, and increasingly in terrestrial radio broadcasts.
[src:columnar-format/data-compression] Lossy compression typically achieves far greater compression than lossless compression, by discarding less-critical data based on psychoacoustic optimizations.
[src:columnar-format/data-compression] Psychoacoustics recognizes that not all data in an audio stream can be perceived by the human auditory system.
[src:columnar-format/data-compression] Most lossy compression reduces redundancy by first identifying perceptually irrelevant sounds, that is, sounds that are very hard to hear.
[src:columnar-format/data-compression] Typical examples include high frequencies or sounds that occur at the same time as louder sounds.
[src:columnar-format/data-compression] Those irrelevant sounds are coded with decreased accuracy or not at all.
[src:columnar-format/data-compression] Due to the nature of lossy algorithms, audio quality suffers a digital generation loss when a file is decompressed and recompressed.
[src:columnar-format/data-compression] This makes lossy compression unsuitable for storing the intermediate results in professional audio engineering applications, such as sound editing and multitrack recording.
[src:columnar-format/data-compression] However, lossy formats such as MP3 are very popular with end-users as the file size is reduced to 5-20% of the original size and a megabyte can store about a minute's worth of music at adequate quality.
[src:columnar-format/data-compression] Several proprietary lossy compression algorithms have been developed that provide higher quality audio performance by using a combination of lossless and lossy algorithms with adaptive bit rates and lower compression ratios.
[src:columnar-format/data-compression] Examples include aptX, LDAC, LHDC, MQA and SCL6.
[src:columnar-format/data-compression] To determine what information in an audio signal is perceptually irrelevant, most lossy compression algorithms use transforms such as the modified discrete cosine transform (MDCT) to convert time domain sampled waveforms into a transform domain, typically the frequency domain.
[src:columnar-format/data-compression] Once transformed, component frequencies can be prioritized according to how audible they are.
[src:columnar-format/data-compression] Equal-loudness contours may also be used to weigh the perceptual importance of components.
[src:columnar-format/data-compression] Models of the human ear-brain combination incorporating such effects are often called psychoacoustic models.
[src:columnar-format/data-compression] Other types of lossy compressors, such as the linear predictive coding (LPC) used with speech, are source-based coders.
[src:columnar-format/data-compression] LPC uses a model of the human vocal tract to analyze speech sounds and infer the parameters used by the model to produce them moment to moment.
[src:columnar-format/data-compression] These changing parameters are transmitted or stored and used to drive another model in the decoder, which reproduces the sound.
[src:columnar-format/data-compression] Lossy formats are often used for the distribution of streaming audio or interactive communication (such as in cell phone networks).
[src:columnar-format/data-compression] In such applications, the data must be decompressed as the data flows, rather than after the entire data stream has been transmitted.
[src:columnar-format/data-compression] Not all audio codecs can be used for streaming applications.
[src:columnar-format/data-compression] Latency is introduced by the methods used to encode and decode the data.
[src:columnar-format/data-compression] Some codecs will analyze a longer segment, called a *frame*, of the data to optimize efficiency, and then code it in a manner that requires a larger segment of data at one time to decode.
[src:columnar-format/data-compression] The inherent latency of the coding algorithm can be critical; for example, when there is a two-way transmission of data, such as with a telephone conversation, significant delays may seriously degrade the perceived quality.
[src:columnar-format/data-compression] In contrast to the speed of compression, which is proportional to the number of operations required by the algorithm, here latency refers to the number of samples that must be analyzed before a block of audio is processed.
[src:columnar-format/data-compression] In the minimum case, latency is zero samples (e.g., if the coder/decoder simply reduces the number of bits used to quantize the signal).
[src:columnar-format/data-compression] Time domain algorithms such as LPC also often have low latencies, hence their popularity in speech coding for telephony.
[src:columnar-format/data-compression] In algorithms such as MP3, however, a large number of samples have to be analyzed to implement a psychoacoustic model in the frequency domain, and latency is on the order of 23 ms.
[src:columnar-format/data-compression] Speech encoding is an important category of audio data compression.
[src:columnar-format/data-compression] The perceptual models used to estimate what aspects of speech a human ear can hear are generally somewhat different from those used for music.
[src:columnar-format/data-compression] The range of frequencies needed to convey the sounds of a human voice is normally far narrower than that needed for music, and the sound is normally less complex.
[src:columnar-format/data-compression] As a result, speech can be encoded at high quality using a relatively low bit rate.
[src:columnar-format/data-compression] The earliest algorithms used in speech encoding (and audio data compression in general) were the A-law algorithm and the μ-law algorithm.
[src:columnar-format/data-compression] Early audio research was conducted at Bell Labs.
[src:columnar-format/data-compression] Chapin Cutler filed the patent on differential pulse-code modulation (DPCM).
[src:columnar-format/data-compression] In 1973, Adaptive DPCM (ADPCM) was introduced by P.
[src:columnar-format/data-compression] Perceptual coding was first used for speech coding compression, with linear predictive coding (LPC).
[src:columnar-format/data-compression] Initial concepts for LPC date back to the work of Fumitada Itakura (Nagoya University) and Shuzo Saito (Nippon Telegraph and Telephone) in 1966.
[src:columnar-format/data-compression] Perceptual coding is used by modern audio compression formats such as MP3 and AAC.
[src:columnar-format/data-compression] Discrete cosine transform (DCT), developed by Nasir Ahmed, T.
[src:columnar-format/data-compression] Rao in 1974, provided the basis for the modified discrete cosine transform (MDCT) used by modern audio compression formats such as MP3, Dolby Digital, and AAC.
[src:columnar-format/data-compression] Bradley in 1987, following earlier work by Princen and Bradley in 1986.
[src:columnar-format/data-compression] The world's first commercial broadcast automation audio compression system was developed by Oscar Bonello, an engineering professor at the University of Buenos Aires.
[src:columnar-format/data-compression] This broadcast automation system was launched in 1987 under the name Audicom.
[src:columnar-format/data-compression] A literature compendium for a large variety of audio coding systems was published in the IEEE's *Journal on Selected Areas in Communications* (*JSAC*), in February 1988.
[src:columnar-format/data-compression] While there were some papers from before that time, this collection documented an entire variety of finished, working audio coders, nearly all of them using perceptual techniques and some kind of frequency analysis and back-end noiseless coding.
[src:columnar-format/data-compression] Uncompressed video requires a very high data rate.
[src:columnar-format/data-compression] Although lossless video compression codecs perform at a compression factor of 5 to 12, a typical H.264 lossy compression video has a compression factor between 20 and 200.
[src:columnar-format/data-compression] The two key video compression techniques used in video coding standards are the DCT and motion compensation (MC).
[src:columnar-format/data-compression] Most video coding standards, such as the H.26x and MPEG formats, typically use motion-compensated DCT video coding (block motion compensation).
[src:columnar-format/data-compression] Most video codecs are used alongside audio compression techniques to store the separate but complementary data streams as one combined package using so-called *container formats*.
[src:columnar-format/data-compression] Video data may be represented as a series of still image frames.
[src:columnar-format/data-compression] Such data usually contains abundant amounts of spatial and temporal redundancy.
[src:columnar-format/data-compression] Video compression algorithms attempt to reduce redundancy and store information more compactly.
[src:columnar-format/data-compression] Most video compression formats and codecs exploit both spatial and temporal redundancy (e.g., through difference coding with motion compensation).
[src:columnar-format/data-compression] Similarities can be encoded by only storing differences between e.g., temporally adjacent frames (inter-frame coding) or spatially adjacent pixels (intra-frame coding).
[src:columnar-format/data-compression] Inter-frame compression (a temporal delta encoding) (re)uses data from one or more earlier or later frames in a sequence to describe the current frame.
[src:columnar-format/data-compression] Intra-frame coding, on the other hand, uses only data from within the current frame, effectively being still-image compression.
[src:columnar-format/data-compression] The intra-frame video coding formats used in camcorders and video editing employ simpler compression that uses only intra-frame prediction.
[src:columnar-format/data-compression] This simplifies video editing software, as it prevents a situation in which a compressed frame refers to data that the editor has deleted.
[src:columnar-format/data-compression] Usually, video compression additionally employs lossy compression techniques like quantization that reduce aspects of the source data that are (more or less) irrelevant to the human visual perception by exploiting perceptual features of human vision.
[src:columnar-format/data-compression] For example, small differences in color are more difficult to perceive than are changes in brightness.
[src:columnar-format/data-compression] Compression algorithms can average a color across these similar areas in a manner similar to those used in JPEG image compression.
[src:columnar-format/data-compression] As in all lossy compression, there is a trade-off between video quality and bit rate, cost of processing the compression and decompression, and system requirements.
[src:columnar-format/data-compression] Highly compressed video may present visible or distracting artifacts.
[src:columnar-format/data-compression] Other methods other than the prevalent DCT-based transform formats, such as fractal compression, matching pursuit and the use of a discrete wavelet transform (DWT), have been the subject of some research, but are typically not used in practical products.
[src:columnar-format/data-compression] Wavelet compression is used in still-image coders and video coders without motion compensation.
[src:columnar-format/data-compression] Interest in fractal compression seems to be waning, due to recent theoretical analysis showing a comparative lack of effectiveness of such methods.
[src:columnar-format/data-compression] In inter-frame coding, individual frames of a video sequence are compared from one frame to the next, and the video compression codec records the differences to the reference frame.
[src:columnar-format/data-compression] If the frame contains areas where nothing has moved, the system can simply issue a short command that copies that part of the previous frame into the next one.
[src:columnar-format/data-compression] If sections of the frame move in a simple manner, the compressor can emit a (slightly longer) command that tells the decompressor to shift, rotate, lighten, or darken the copy.
[src:columnar-format/data-compression] This longer command still remains much shorter than data generated by intra-frame compression.
[src:columnar-format/data-compression] Usually, the encoder will also transmit a residue signal which describes the remaining, more subtle differences to the reference imagery.
[src:columnar-format/data-compression] Using entropy coding, these residue signals have a more compact representation than the full signal.
[src:columnar-format/data-compression] In areas of video with more motion, the compression must encode more data to keep up with the larger number of pixels that are changing.
[src:columnar-format/data-compression] Commonly, the high-frequency detail of explosions, flames, flocks of animals, and some panning shots will lead to decreases in quality or increases in the variable bitrate.
[src:columnar-format/data-compression] Many commonly used video compression methods (e.g., those in standards approved by the ITU-T or ISO) share the same basic architecture that dates back to H.261, which was standardized in 1988 by the ITU-T.
[src:columnar-format/data-compression] They mostly rely on the DCT, applied to rectangular blocks of neighboring pixels, and temporal prediction using motion vectors, as well as nowadays also an in-loop filtering step.
[src:columnar-format/data-compression] In the prediction stage, various deduplication and difference-coding techniques are applied that help decorrelate data and describe new data based on already transmitted data.
[src:columnar-format/data-compression] Then, rectangular blocks of remaining pixel data are transformed to the frequency domain.
[src:columnar-format/data-compression] In the main lossy processing stage, frequency domain data gets quantized in order to reduce information that is irrelevant to human visual perception.
[src:columnar-format/data-compression] In the last stage, statistical redundancy gets largely eliminated by an entropy coder, which often applies some form of arithmetic coding.
[src:columnar-format/data-compression] In an additional in-loop filtering stage, various filters can be applied to the reconstructed image signal.
[src:columnar-format/data-compression] By computing these filters also inside the encoding loop, they can help compression because they can be applied to reference material before it gets used in the prediction process and they can be guided using the original signal.
[src:columnar-format/data-compression] The most popular example are deblocking filters that blur out blocking artifacts from quantization discontinuities at transform block boundaries.
[src:columnar-format/data-compression] Cherry proposed a run-length encoding bandwidth compression scheme for the transmission of analog television signals.
[src:columnar-format/data-compression] The DCT, which is fundamental to modern video compression, was introduced by Nasir Ahmed, T.
[src:columnar-format/data-compression] H.261, which debuted in 1988, commercially introduced the prevalent basic architecture of video compression technology.
[src:columnar-format/data-compression] It was the first video coding format based on DCT compression.
[src:columnar-format/data-compression] H.261 was developed by a number of companies, including Hitachi, PictureTel, NTT, BT and Toshiba.
[src:columnar-format/data-compression] The most popular video coding standards used for codecs have been the MPEG standards.
[src:columnar-format/data-compression] MPEG-1 was developed by the Motion Picture Experts Group (MPEG) in 1991, and it was designed to compress VHS-quality video.
[src:columnar-format/data-compression] It was succeeded in 1994 by MPEG-2/H.262, which was developed by a number of companies, primarily Sony, Thomson and Mitsubishi Electric.
[src:columnar-format/data-compression] MPEG-2 became the standard video format for DVD and SD digital television.
[src:columnar-format/data-compression] It was also developed by a number of companies, primarily Mitsubishi Electric, Hitachi and Panasonic.
[src:columnar-format/data-compression] H.264/MPEG-4 AVC was developed in 2003 by a number of organizations, primarily Panasonic, Godo Kaisha IP Bridge and LG Electronics.
[src:columnar-format/data-compression] AVC commercially introduced the modern context-adaptive binary arithmetic coding (CABAC) and context-adaptive variable-length coding (CAVLC) algorithms.
[src:columnar-format/data-compression] Genetics compression algorithms are the latest generation of lossless algorithms that compress data (typically sequences of nucleotides) using both conventional compression algorithms and genetic algorithms adapted to the specific datatype.
[src:columnar-format/data-compression] In 2012, a team of scientists from Johns Hopkins University published a genetic compression algorithm that does not use a reference genome for compression.
[src:columnar-format/data-compression] HAPZIPPER was tailored for HapMap data and achieves over 20-fold compression (95% reduction in file size), providing 2- to 4-fold better compression and is less computationally intensive than the leading general-purpose compression utilities.
[src:columnar-format/data-compression] For this, Chanda, Elhaik, and Bader introduced MAF-based encoding (MAFE), which reduces the heterogeneity of the dataset by sorting SNPs by their minor allele frequency, thus homogenizing the dataset.
[src:columnar-format/data-compression] Other algorithms developed in 2009 and 2013 (DNAZip and GenomeZip) have compression ratios of up to 1200-fold—allowing 6 billion basepair diploid human genomes to be stored in 2.5 megabytes (relative to a reference genome or averaged over many genomes).
[src:columnar-format/data-compression] It is estimated that the total amount of data that is stored on the world's storage devices could be further compressed with existing compression algorithms by a remaining average factor of 4.5:1.
[src:columnar-format/data-compression] It is estimated that the combined technological capacity of the world to store information provides 1,300 exabytes of hardware digits in 2007, but when the corresponding content is optimally compressed, this only represents 295 exabytes of Shannon information.
[src:columnar-format/database-index] A **database index** is a data structure that improves the speed of data retrieval operations on a database table at the cost of additional writes and storage space to maintain the index data structure.
[src:columnar-format/database-index] Indexes are used to quickly locate data without having to search every row in a database table every time said table is accessed.
[src:columnar-format/database-index] Indexes can be created using one or more columns of a database table, providing the basis for both rapid random lookups and efficient access of ordered records.
[src:columnar-format/database-index] An index is a copy of selected columns of data, from a table, that is designed to enable very efficient search.
[src:columnar-format/database-index] An index normally includes a "key" or direct link to the original row of data from which it was copied, to allow the complete row to be retrieved efficiently.
[src:columnar-format/database-index] Some databases extend the power of indexing by letting developers create indexes on column values that have been transformed by functions or expressions.
[src:columnar-format/database-index] For example, an index could be created on `upper(last_name)`, which would only store the upper-case versions of the `last_name` field in the index.
[src:columnar-format/database-index] Another option sometimes supported is the use of partial index, where index entries are created only for those records that satisfy some conditional expression.
[src:columnar-format/database-index] A further aspect of flexibility is to permit indexing on user-defined functions, as well as expressions formed from an assortment of built-in functions.
[src:columnar-format/database-index] Most database software includes indexing technology that enables sub-linear time lookup to improve performance, as linear search is inefficient for large databases.
[src:columnar-format/database-index] Suppose a database contains N data items and one must be retrieved based on the value of one of the fields.
[src:columnar-format/database-index] A simple implementation retrieves and examines each item according to the test.
[src:columnar-format/database-index] If there is only one matching item, this can stop when it finds that single item, but if there are multiple matches, it must test everything.
[src:columnar-format/database-index] This means that the number of operations in the average case is O(N) or linear time.
[src:columnar-format/database-index] Since databases may contain many objects, and since lookup is a common operation, it is often desirable to improve performance.
[src:columnar-format/database-index] An index is any data structure that improves the performance of lookup.
[src:columnar-format/database-index] There are many different data structures used for this purpose.
[src:columnar-format/database-index] There are complex design trade-offs involving lookup performance, index size, and index-update performance.
[src:columnar-format/database-index] Many index designs exhibit logarithmic (O(log(N))) lookup performance and in some applications it is possible to achieve flat (O(1)) performance.
[src:columnar-format/database-index] Indexes are used to police database constraints, such as UNIQUE, EXCLUSION, PRIMARY KEY and FOREIGN KEY.
[src:columnar-format/database-index] An index may be declared as UNIQUE, which creates an implicit constraint on the underlying table.
[src:columnar-format/database-index] Database systems usually implicitly create an index on a set of columns declared PRIMARY KEY, and some are capable of using an already-existing index to police this constraint.
[src:columnar-format/database-index] Many database systems require that both referencing and referenced sets of columns in a FOREIGN KEY constraint are indexed, thus improving performance of inserts, updates and deletes to the tables participating in the constraint.
[src:columnar-format/database-index] Some database systems support an EXCLUSION constraint that ensures that, for a newly inserted or updated record, a certain predicate holds for no other record.
[src:columnar-format/database-index] This can be used to implement a UNIQUE constraint (with equality predicate) or more complex constraints, like ensuring that no overlapping time ranges or no intersecting geometry objects would be stored in the table.
[src:columnar-format/database-index] An index supporting fast searching for records satisfying the predicate is required to police such a constraint.
[src:columnar-format/database-index] The data is present in arbitrary order, but the **logical ordering** is specified by the index.
[src:columnar-format/database-index] The data rows may be spread throughout the table regardless of the value of the indexed column or expression.
[src:columnar-format/database-index] The non-clustered index tree contains the index keys in sorted order, with the leaf level of the index containing the pointer to the record (page and the row number in the data page in page-organized engines; row offset in file-organized engines).
[src:columnar-format/database-index] There can be more than one non-clustered index on a database table.
[src:columnar-format/database-index] Clustering alters the data block into a certain distinct order to match the index, resulting in the row data being stored in order.
[src:columnar-format/database-index] Therefore, only one clustered index can be created on a given database table.
[src:columnar-format/database-index] Clustered indexes can greatly increase overall speed of retrieval, but usually only where the data is accessed sequentially in the same or reverse order of the clustered index, or when a range of items is selected.
[src:columnar-format/database-index] Since the physical records are in this sort order on disk, the next row item in the sequence is immediately before or after the last one, and so fewer data block reads are required.
[src:columnar-format/database-index] The primary feature of a clustered index is therefore the ordering of the physical data rows in accordance with the index blocks that point to them.
[src:columnar-format/database-index] Some databases separate the data and index blocks into separate files, others put two completely different data blocks within the same physical file(s).
[src:columnar-format/database-index] When multiple databases and multiple tables are joined, it is called a **cluster** (not to be confused with clustered index described previously).
[src:columnar-format/database-index] The records for the tables sharing the value of a cluster key shall be stored together in the same or nearby data blocks.
[src:columnar-format/database-index] This may improve the joins of these tables on the cluster key, since the matching records are stored together and less I/O is required to locate them.
[src:columnar-format/database-index] The cluster configuration defines the data layout in the tables that are parts of the cluster.
[src:columnar-format/database-index] A cluster can be keyed with a B-tree index or a hash table.
[src:columnar-format/database-index] The data block where the table record is stored is defined by the value of the cluster key.
[src:columnar-format/database-index] The order that the index definition defines the columns in is important.
[src:columnar-format/database-index] It is possible to retrieve a set of row identifiers using only the first indexed column.
[src:columnar-format/database-index] However, it is not possible or efficient (on most databases) to retrieve the set of row identifiers using only the second or greater indexed column.
[src:columnar-format/database-index] For example, in a phone book organized by city first, then by last name, and then by first name, in a particular city, one can easily extract the list of all phone numbers.
[src:columnar-format/database-index] However, it would be very tedious to find all the phone numbers for a particular last name.
[src:columnar-format/database-index] One would have to look within each city's section for the entries with that last name.
[src:columnar-format/database-index] Some databases can do this, others just won't use the index.
[src:columnar-format/database-index] Then a sequential lookup checks the matching with `first_name`.
[src:columnar-format/database-index] So, to improve the performance, one must ensure that the index is created on the order of search columns.
[src:columnar-format/database-index] Indexes are useful for many applications but come with some limitations.
[src:columnar-format/database-index] Consider the following SQL statement: `SELECT first_name FROM people WHERE last_name = 'Smith';`.
[src:columnar-format/database-index] To process this statement without an index the database software must look at the last_name column on every row in the table (this is known as a full table scan).
[src:columnar-format/database-index] With an index the database simply follows the index data structure (typically a B-tree) until the Smith entry has been found; this is much less computationally expensive than a full table scan.
[src:columnar-format/database-index] Consider this SQL statement: `SELECT email_address FROM customers WHERE email_address LIKE '%@wikipedia.org';`.
[src:columnar-format/database-index] This query would yield an email address for every customer whose email address ends with "@wikipedia.org", but even if the email_address column has been indexed the database must perform a full index scan.
[src:columnar-format/database-index] This is because the index is built with the assumption that words go from left to right.
[src:columnar-format/database-index] With a wildcard at the beginning of the search-term, the database software is unable to use the underlying index data structure (in other words, the WHERE-clause is *not sargable*).
[src:columnar-format/database-index] This problem can be solved through the addition of another index created on `reverse(email_address)` and a SQL query like this: `SELECT email_address FROM customers WHERE reverse(email_address) LIKE reverse('%@wikipedia.org');`.
[src:columnar-format/database-index] This puts the wild-card at the right-most part of the query (now gro.aidepikiw@%), which the index on reverse(email_address) can satisfy.
[src:columnar-format/database-index] When the wildcard characters are used on both sides of the search word as *%wikipedia.org%*, the index available on this field is not used.
[src:columnar-format/database-index] Rather only a sequential search is performed, which takes ⁠ $O(N)$ ⁠ time.
[src:columnar-format/database-index] To mitigate this, a full-text indexing approach can be used.
[src:columnar-format/database-index] A bitmap index is a special kind of indexing that stores the bulk of its data as bit arrays (bitmaps) and answers most queries by performing bitwise logical operations on these bitmaps.
[src:columnar-format/database-index] The most commonly used indexes, such as B+ trees, are most efficient if the values they index do not repeat or repeat a small number of times.
[src:columnar-format/database-index] In contrast, the bitmap index is designed for cases where the values of a variable repeat very frequently.
[src:columnar-format/database-index] For example, the sex field in a customer database usually contains at most three distinct values: male, female or unknown (not recorded).
[src:columnar-format/database-index] For such variables, the bitmap index can have a significant performance advantage over the commonly used trees.
[src:columnar-format/database-index] A dense index in databases is a file with pairs of keys and pointers for every record in the data file.
[src:columnar-format/database-index] Every key in this file is associated with a particular pointer to *a record* in the sorted data file.
[src:columnar-format/database-index] In clustered indices with duplicate keys, the dense index points *to the first record* with that key.
[src:columnar-format/database-index] A sparse index in databases is a file with pairs of keys and pointers for every block in the data file.
[src:columnar-format/database-index] Every key in this file is associated with a particular pointer *to the block* in the sorted data file.
[src:columnar-format/database-index] In clustered indices with duplicate keys, the sparse index points *to the lowest search key* in each block.
[src:columnar-format/database-index] A reverse-key index reverses the key value before entering it in the index.
[src:columnar-format/database-index] Reversing the key value is particularly useful for indexing data such as sequence numbers, where new key values monotonically increase.
[src:columnar-format/database-index] An inverted index maps a content word to the document containing it, thereby allowing full-text searches.
[src:columnar-format/database-index] The primary index contains the key fields of the table and a pointer to the non-key fields of the table.
[src:columnar-format/database-index] The primary index is created automatically when the table is created in the database.
[src:columnar-format/database-index] It is used to index fields that are neither ordering fields nor key fields (there is no assurance that the file is organized on key field or primary key field).
[src:columnar-format/database-index] One index entry for every tuple in the data file (dense index) contains the value of the indexed attribute and pointer to the block or record.
[src:columnar-format/database-index] Another type of index used in database systems is linear hashing.
[src:columnar-format/database-index] Indices can be implemented using a variety of data structures.
[src:columnar-format/database-index] Popular indices include balanced trees, B+ trees and hashes.
[src:columnar-format/database-index] In Microsoft SQL Server, the leaf node of the clustered index corresponds to the actual data, not simply a pointer to data that resides elsewhere, as is the case with a non-clustered index.
[src:columnar-format/database-index] Each relation can have a single clustered index and many unclustered indices.
[src:columnar-format/database-index] An index is typically being accessed concurrently by several transactions and processes, and thus needs concurrency control.
[src:columnar-format/database-index] While in principle indexes can utilize the common database concurrency control methods, specialized concurrency control methods for indexes exist, which are applied in conjunction with the common methods for a substantial performance gain.
[src:columnar-format/database-index] In most cases, an index is used to quickly locate the data records from which the required data is read.
[src:columnar-format/database-index] In other words, the index is only used to locate data records in the table and not to return data.
[src:columnar-format/database-index] A covering index is a special case where the index itself contains the required data fields and can answer the required data.
[src:columnar-format/database-index] To find the Name for ID 13, an index on (ID) is useful, but the record must still be read to get the Name.
[src:columnar-format/database-index] However, an index on (ID, Name) contains the required data field and eliminates the need to look up the record.
[src:columnar-format/database-index] Covering indexes are each for a specific table.
[src:columnar-format/database-index] Queries which JOIN/ access across multiple tables, may potentially consider covering indexes on more than one of these tables.
[src:columnar-format/database-index] A covering index can dramatically speed up data retrieval but may itself be large due to the additional keys, which slow down data insertion and update.
[src:columnar-format/database-index] To reduce such index size, some systems allow including non-key fields in the index.
[src:columnar-format/database-index] Non-key fields are not themselves part of the index ordering but only included at the leaf level, allowing for a covering index with less overall index size.
[src:columnar-format/database-index] This can be done in SQL with `CREATE INDEX my_index ON my_table (id) INCLUDE (name);`.
[src:columnar-format/database-index] No standard defines how to create indexes, because the ISO SQL Standard does not cover physical aspects.
[src:columnar-format/database-index] Indexes are one of the physical parts of database conception among others like storage (tablespace or filegroups).
[src:columnar-format/database-index] RDBMS vendors all give a `CREATE INDEX` syntax with some specific options that depend on their software's capabilities.
[src:columnar-format/simd] Such machines exploit data level parallelism, but not concurrency: there are simultaneous (parallel) computations, but each unit performs exactly the same instruction at any given moment (just with different data).
[src:columnar-format/simd] A simple example is to add many pairs of numbers together, all of the SIMD units are performing an addition, but each one has different pairs of values to add.
[src:columnar-format/simd] SIMD is especially applicable to common tasks such as adjusting the contrast in a digital image or adjusting the volume of digital audio.
[src:columnar-format/simd] Most modern central processing unit (CPU) designs include SIMD instructions to improve the performance of multimedia use.
[src:columnar-format/simd] In recent CPUs, SIMD units are tightly coupled with cache hierarchies and prefetch mechanisms, which minimize latency during large block operations.
[src:columnar-format/simd] For instance, AVX-512-enabled processors can prefetch entire cache lines and apply fused multiply-add operations (FMA) in a single SIMD cycle.
[src:columnar-format/simd] SIMD has three different subcategories in Flynn's 1972 Taxonomy, one of which is single instruction, multiple threads (SIMT).
[src:columnar-format/simd] SIMT should not be confused with software threads or hardware threads, both of which are task time-sharing (time-slicing).
[src:columnar-format/simd] SIMT is true simultaneous parallel hardware-level execution, such as in the ILLIAC IV.
[src:columnar-format/simd] SIMD should not be confused with Vector processing, characterized by the Cray 1 and clarified in Duncan's taxonomy.
[src:columnar-format/simd] The difference between SIMD and vector processors is primarily the presence of a Cray-style `SET VECTOR LENGTH` instruction.
[src:columnar-format/simd] The first known operational use to date of SIMD within a register was the TX-2, in 1958.
[src:columnar-format/simd] It was capable of 36-bit operations and two 18-bit or four 9-bit sub-word operations.
[src:columnar-format/simd] The first commercial use of SIMD instructions was in the ILLIAC IV, which was completed in 1972.
[src:columnar-format/simd] Vector supercomputers of the early 1970s such as the CDC Star-100 and the Texas Instruments ASC could operate on a "vector" of data with a single instruction.
[src:columnar-format/simd] Vector processing was especially popularized by Cray in the 1970s and 1980s.
[src:columnar-format/simd] Vector processing architectures are now considered separate from SIMD computers: Duncan's Taxonomy includes them whereas Flynn's Taxonomy does not, due to Flynn's work (1966, 1972) pre-dating the Cray-1 (1977).
[src:columnar-format/simd] The complexity of Vector processors however inspired a simpler arrangement known as SIMD within a register.
[src:columnar-format/simd] The first era of modern SIMD computers was characterized by massively parallel processing-style supercomputers such as the Thinking Machines Connection Machine CM-1 and CM-2.
[src:columnar-format/simd] These computers had many limited-functionality processors that would work in parallel.
[src:columnar-format/simd] For example, each of 65,536 single-bit processors in a Thinking Machines CM-2 would execute the same instruction at the same time, allowing, for instance, to logically combine 65,536 pairs of bits at a time, using a hypercube-connected network or processor-dedicated RAM to find its operands.
[src:columnar-format/simd] Supercomputing moved away from the SIMD approach when inexpensive scalar multiple instruction, multiple data (MIMD) approaches based on commodity processors such as the Intel i860 XP became more powerful, and interest in SIMD waned.
[src:columnar-format/simd] The current era of SIMD processors grew out of the desktop-computer market rather than the supercomputer market.
[src:columnar-format/simd] As desktop processors became powerful enough to support real-time gaming and audio/video processing during the 1990s, demand grew for this type of computing power, and microprocessor vendors turned to SIMD to meet the demand.
[src:columnar-format/simd] This resurgence also coincided with the rise of DirectX and OpenGL shader models, which heavily leveraged SIMD under the hood.
[src:columnar-format/simd] The graphics APIs encouraged programmers to adopt data-parallel programming styles, indirectly accelerating SIMD adoption in desktop software.
[src:columnar-format/simd] Hewlett-Packard introduced Multimedia Acceleration eXtensions (MAX) instructions into PA-RISC 1.1 desktops in 1994 to accelerate MPEG decoding.
[src:columnar-format/simd] Sun Microsystems introduced SIMD integer instructions in its "VIS" instruction set extensions in 1995, in its UltraSPARC I microprocessor.
[src:columnar-format/simd] MIPS followed suit with their similar MDMX system.
[src:columnar-format/simd] The first widely deployed desktop SIMD was with Intel's MMX extensions to the x86 architecture in 1996.
[src:columnar-format/simd] This sparked the introduction of the much more powerful AltiVec system in the Motorola PowerPC and IBM's POWER systems.
[src:columnar-format/simd] Intel responded in 1999 by introducing the all-new SSE system.
[src:columnar-format/simd] Since then, there have been several extensions to the SIMD instruction sets for both architectures.
[src:columnar-format/simd] Advanced vector extensions AVX, AVX2 and AVX-512 are developed by Intel.
[src:columnar-format/simd] AMD supports AVX, AVX2, and AVX-512 in their current products.
[src:columnar-format/simd] With SIMD, an order of magnitude increase in code size is not uncommon, when compared to equivalent scalar or equivalent vector code, and an order of magnitude *or greater* effectiveness (work done per instruction) is achievable with Vector ISAs.
[src:columnar-format/simd] ARM's Scalable Vector Extension takes another approach, known in Flynn's Taxonomy more commonly known today as "Predicated" (masked) SIMD.
[src:columnar-format/simd] This approach is not as compact as vector processing but is still far better than non-predicated SIMD.
[src:columnar-format/simd] Detailed comparative examples are given at Vector processor § Vector instruction example.
[src:columnar-format/simd] Small-scale (64 or 128 bits) SIMD became popular on general-purpose CPUs in the early 1990s and continued through 1997 and later with Motion Video Instructions (MVI) for Alpha.
[src:columnar-format/simd] Intel's AVX-512 SIMD instructions process 512 bits of data at once.
[src:columnar-format/simd] The IBM, Sony, Toshiba co-developed Cell processor's Synergistic Processing Element's (SPE's) instruction set is heavily SIMD based.
[src:columnar-format/simd] AMD GPUs since the TeraScale (microarchitecture) are SIMD-based, a feature that has remained in the 2020s microartectures RDNA and CDNA, with a layer of single instruction, multiple threads (SIMT) above.
[src:columnar-format/simd] On the other hand, Nvidia's CUDA architectures use scalar cores with SIMT.
[src:columnar-format/simd] Philips, now NXP, developed several SIMD processors named Xetal.
[src:columnar-format/simd] The Xetal has 320 16-bit processor elements especially designed for vision tasks.
[src:columnar-format/simd] Apple's M1 and M2 chips also incorporate SIMD units deeply integrated with their GPU and Neural Engine, using Apple-designed SIMD pipelines optimized for image filtering, convolution, and matrix multiplication.
[src:columnar-format/simd] This unified memory architecture helps SIMD instructions operate on shared memory pools more efficiently.
[src:columnar-format/simd] (The CPU part implements ordinary NEON).
[src:columnar-format/simd] SIMD instructions are widely used to process 3D graphics, although modern graphics cards with embedded SIMD have largely taken over this task from the CPU.
[src:columnar-format/simd] Some systems also include permute functions that re-pack elements inside vectors, making them especially useful for data processing and compression.
[src:columnar-format/simd] The trend of general-purpose computing on GPUs (GPGPU) may lead to wider use of SIMD in the future.
[src:columnar-format/simd] Recent compilers such as LLVM, GNU Compiler Collection (GCC), and Intel's ICC offer aggressive auto-vectoring options.
[src:columnar-format/simd] Developers can often enable these with flags like `-O3` or `-ftree-vectorize`, which guide the compiler to restructure loops for SIMD compatibility.
[src:columnar-format/simd] Adoption of SIMD systems in personal computer software was at first slow, due to a number of problems.
[src:columnar-format/simd] One was that many of the early SIMD instruction sets tended to slow overall performance of the system due to the re-use of existing floating point registers.
[src:columnar-format/simd] Other systems, like MMX and 3DNow!, offered support for data types that were not interesting to a wide audience and had expensive context switching instructions to switch between using the FPU and MMX registers.
[src:columnar-format/simd] Compilers also often lacked support, requiring programmers to resort to assembly language coding.
[src:columnar-format/simd] The introduction of 3DNow! by AMD and SSE by Intel confused matters somewhat, but today the system seems to have settled down (after AMD adopted SSE) and newer compilers should result in more SIMD-enabled software.
[src:columnar-format/simd] Intel and AMD now both provide optimized math libraries that use SIMD instructions, and open source alternatives like libSIMD, SIMDx86 and SLEEF have started to appear (see also libm).
[src:columnar-format/simd] Apple Computer had somewhat more success, even though they entered the SIMD market later than the rest.
[src:columnar-format/simd] AltiVec offered a rich system and can be programmed using increasingly sophisticated compilers from Motorola, IBM and GNU, therefore assembly language programming is rarely needed.
[src:columnar-format/simd] Additionally, many of the systems that would benefit from SIMD were supplied by Apple itself, for example iTunes and QuickTime.
[src:columnar-format/simd] However, in 2006, Apple computers moved to Intel x86 processors.
[src:columnar-format/simd] Apple's APIs and development tools (XCode) were modified to support SSE2 and SSE3 as well as AltiVec.
[src:columnar-format/simd] Apple was the dominant purchaser of PowerPC chips from IBM and Freescale Semiconductor.
[src:columnar-format/simd] Even though Apple has stopped using PowerPC processors in their products, further development of AltiVec is continued in several PowerPC and Power ISA designs from Freescale and IBM.
[src:columnar-format/simd] It is common for publishers of the SIMD instruction sets to make their own C and C++ language extensions with intrinsic functions or special datatypes (with operator overloading) guaranteeing the generation of vector code.
[src:columnar-format/simd] Intel, AltiVec, and ARM NEON provide extensions widely adopted by the compilers targeting their CPUs.
[src:columnar-format/simd] The GNU C Compiler takes the extensions a step further by abstracting them into a universal interface that can be used on any platform by providing a way of defining SIMD datatypes.
[src:columnar-format/simd] The LLVM Clang compiler also implements the feature, with an analogous interface defined in the IR.
[src:columnar-format/simd] Rust's `packed_simd` crate (and the experimental `std::simd`) uses this interface, and so does Swift 2.0+.
[src:columnar-format/simd] C++ has an experimental interface `std::experimental::simd` that works similarly to the GCC extension.
[src:columnar-format/simd] For GCC and libstdc++, a wrapper library that builds on top of the GCC extension is available.
[src:columnar-format/simd] The `System.Numerics.Vector` package, available on NuGet, implements SIMD datatypes.
[src:columnar-format/simd] Java also has a new proposed API for SIMD instructions available in OpenJDK 17 in an incubator module.
[src:columnar-format/simd] It also has a safe fallback mechanism on unsupported CPUs to simple loops.
[src:columnar-format/simd] Instead of providing an SIMD datatype, compilers can also be hinted to auto-vectorize some loops, potentially taking some assertions about the lack of data dependency.
[src:columnar-format/simd] This is not as flexible as manipulating SIMD variables directly, but is easier to use.
[src:columnar-format/simd] OpenMP 4.0+ has a `#pragma omp simd` hint.
[src:columnar-format/simd] This OpenMP interface has replaced a wide set of nonstandard extensions, including Cilk's `#pragma simd`, GCC's `#pragma GCC ivdep`, and many more.
[src:columnar-format/simd] "SIMD everywhere", a collection of C/C++ headers implementing platform-specific intrinsics for other platforms (e.g.
[src:columnar-format/simd] SSE intrinsics for ARM NEON), includes the use of platform-specific intrinsics, generic vector interfaces, and vectorization hints.
[src:columnar-format/simd] It can be used as a "Rosetta Stone" for comparing these different SIMD programming paradigms.
[src:columnar-format/simd] Another approach is SPMD: write a program that looks as if it operates only one element on the time, then have a compiler widen it to match the SIMD vector width.
[src:columnar-format/simd] This is the approach used by graphics shaders and more recently adopted by CPU-oriented tools such as Intel IPSC.
[src:columnar-format/simd] Consumer software is typically expected to work on a range of CPUs covering multiple generations, which could limit the programmer's ability to use new SIMD instructions to improve the computational performance of a program.
[src:columnar-format/simd] The solution is to include multiple versions of the same code that uses either older or newer SIMD technologies, and pick one that best fits the user's CPU at run-time (dynamic dispatch).
[src:columnar-format/simd] FMV, manually coded in assembly language, is quite commonly used in a number of performance-critical libraries such as glibc and libjpeg-turbo.
[src:columnar-format/simd] Intel C++ Compiler, GNU Compiler Collection since GCC 6, and Clang since clang 7 allow for a simplified approach, with the compiler taking care of function duplication and selection.
[src:columnar-format/simd] GCC and clang requires explicit `target_clones` labels in the code to "clone" functions, while ICC does so automatically (under the command-line option `/Qax`).
[src:columnar-format/simd] The Rust programming language also supports FMV.
[src:columnar-format/simd] The setup is similar to GCC and Clang in that the code defines what instruction sets to compile for, but cloning is manually done via inlining.
[src:columnar-format/simd] As using FMV requires code modification on GCC and Clang, vendors more commonly use library multi-versioning: this is easier to achieve as only compiler switches need to be changed.
[src:columnar-format/simd] Glibc supports LMV and this functionality is adopted by the Intel-backed Clear Linux project.
[src:columnar-format/simd] In 2013 John McCutchan announced that he had created a high-performance interface to SIMD instruction sets for the Dart programming language, bringing the benefits of SIMD to web programs for the first time.
[src:columnar-format/simd] Instances of these types are immutable and in optimized code are mapped directly to SIMD registers.
[src:columnar-format/simd] Operations expressed in Dart typically are compiled into a single instruction without any overhead.
[src:columnar-format/simd] This is similar to C and C++ intrinsics.
[src:columnar-format/simd] Benchmarks for 4×4 matrix multiplication, 3D vertex transformation, and Mandelbrot set visualization show near 400% speedup compared to scalar code written in Dart.
[src:columnar-format/simd] Intel announced at IDF 2013 that they were implementing McCutchan's specification for both V8 and SpiderMonkey.
[src:columnar-format/simd] However, by 2017, SIMD.js was taken out of the ECMAScript standard queue in favor of pursuing a similar interface in WebAssembly.
[src:columnar-format/simd] Support for SIMD was added to the WebAssembly 2.0 specification, which was finished on 2022 and became official in December 2024.
[src:columnar-format/simd] LLVM's autovectoring, when compiling C or C++ to WebAssembly, can target WebAssembly SIMD to automatically make use of SIMD, while SIMD intrinsic are also available.
[src:columnar-format/simd] It has generally proven difficult to find sustainable commercial applications for SIMD-only processors in general-purpose computing.
[src:columnar-format/simd] One that has had some measure of success is the GAPP, which was developed by Lockheed Martin and taken to the commercial sector by their spin-off Teranex.
[src:columnar-format/simd] A more ubiquitous application for SIMD is found in video games: nearly every modern video game console since 1998 has incorporated a SIMD processor somewhere in its architecture.
[src:columnar-format/simd] The PlayStation 2 was unusual in that one of its vector-float units could function as an autonomous digital signal processor (DSP) executing its own instruction stream, or as a coprocessor driven by ordinary CPU instructions.
[src:columnar-format/simd] 3D graphics applications tend to lend themselves well to SIMD processing as they rely heavily on operations with 4-dimensional vectors.
[src:columnar-format/simd] Microsoft's Direct3D 9.0 now chooses at runtime processor-specific implementations of its own math operations, including the use of SIMD-capable instructions.
[src:columnar-format/simd] A later processor that used vector processing is the Cell processor used in the PlayStation 3, which was developed by IBM in cooperation with Toshiba and Sony.
[src:columnar-format/simd] It uses a number of SIMD processors (a non-uniform memory access (NUMA) architecture, each with independent local store and controlled by a general purpose CPU) and is geared towards the huge datasets required by 3D and video processing applications.
[src:columnar-format/simd] It differs from traditional ISAs by being SIMD from the ground up with no separate scalar registers.
[src:columnar-format/simd] Ziilabs produced an SIMD type processor for use on mobile devices, such as media players and mobile phones.
[src:columnar-format/simd] Larger scale commercial SIMD processors are available from ClearSpeed Technology, Ltd. and Stream Processors, Inc.
[src:columnar-format/simd] ClearSpeed's CSX600 (2004) has 96 cores each with two double-precision floating point units while the CSX700 (2008) has 192.
[src:columnar-format/simd] Stream Processors is headed by computer architect Bill Dally.
[src:columnar-format/simd] Their Storm-1 processor (2007) contains 80 SIMD cores controlled by a MIPS CPU.
